div.div: The SAT, or separating axis theory, states that any two polygons are not colliding if any given axis can be found that separates them.
This can be calculated by generating a list of axes, which in this case can be done by iterating through all edges in the two shapes and calculating the perpendicular.
These axes are then iterated through, and the offset between the axis and two shapes is determined using the minimum and maximum vectors for each shape.
If this offset is 0, or less than 0, we know that the axis separates the two shapes, and we can return immediately; there is no collision between the shapes.
If o is less than mtv_overlap, which is set to infinity, we set the overlap to o and the axis to axis.
We then check if this statement ran, as mtv_overlap was initialized as None outside the statement. If it is, we set the axis to negative
if the difference in the two bodies position is negative.
We can then determine the contact point adding the positions and multiplying it by 0.5.
